  "text": "there was a strong relationship between the number of times a woodrat was trapped and reproductive success, suggesting that males trapped more frequently were more active in general and may also have been more active in pursuing females. Unlike [CITATION_1] , we found no strong evidence that males with greater changes in mass had higher reproductive success. This may have been due to our small sample size or low variation in mass change, with most males having a positive mass change over the season. Furthermore, the lack of any significant partial correlation for factors of male-male competition suggests that intrasexual competition does not dictate mating patterns in woodrats.",
